{
  "text": "Cx43 is the major structural protein of ventricular gap junctions, and a significant decrease in Cx43 causes sudden arrhythmic death. [CITATION_1] In this study, we showed that cardiac RAS activation, as occurs in heart failure, [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] was associated with a significant reduction in Cx43. This range of reduction in Cx43 is known to be arrhythmogenic. [CITATION_4] These experiments establish that AngII-mediated ROS plays a role in ventricular arrhythmogenesis, that the mitochondria are the principal source of ROS leading to the arrhythmic substrate, and that ROS is arrhythmogenic, at least in part, by altering Cx43 probably by ROS activation of c-Src. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] Although ROS have been implicated in the genesis of arrhythmia, [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] translation of those findings to clinical studies using general ROS scavengers, such as vitamin E and C, has not produced impressive results. [CITATION_12] In our study, only a mitochondria-targeted antioxidant was able to prevent arrhythmia. Targeting other known cardiac sources of ROS or using a general antioxidant was ineffective despite dosages and routes of administration that have been shown to be effective in inhibition of the targeted source of ROS production. [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] This result, particularly the therapeutic difference between TEMPOL and MitoTEMPO treatments, suggests that AngII-mediated ROS production is highly compartmentalized within mitochondria in cardiomyocytes.",
  "correct_citation": {
